04476nam a22006735i 9780226437682DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264376827 a10.7208/97802264376822doi  a(DE-B1597)524808  a(OCoLC)968731413  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHV1347b.C44 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.23086/945223  aLC 565472rvk1 aCheney, Kristen E., eauthor.10aCrying for Our Elders :bAfrican Orphanhood in the Age of HIV and AIDS /cKristen E. Cheney. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Generations of HIV/AIDS, Orphanhood, and Intervention -- tPart Two. Beyond Checking the "Voice" Box: Children's Rights and Participation in Development and Research -- tPart Three. Orphanhood in the Age of HIV and AIDS -- tPart Four. Blood Binds: The Transformation of Kinship and the Politics of Adoption -- tPart Five. Conclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Children and Household Profiles by Youth Research Assistant Focus Group, 2007-2009 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe HIV/AIDS epidemic in Africa has defined the childhoods of an entire generation. Over the past twenty years, international NGOs and charities have devoted immense attention to the millions of African children orphaned by the disease. But in Crying for Our Elders, anthropologist Kristen E. Cheney argues that these humanitarian groups have misread the 'orphan crisis'. She explains how the global humanitarian focus on orphanhood often elides the social and political circumstances that actually present the greatest adversity to vulnerable children-in effect deepening the crisis and thereby affecting children's lives as irrevocably as HIV/AIDS itself.   Through ethnographic fieldwork and collaborative research with children in Uganda, Cheney traces how the "best interest" principle that governs children's' rights can stigmatize orphans and leave children in the post-antiretroviral era even more vulnerable to exploitation. She details the dramatic effects this has on traditional family support and child protection and stresses child empowerment over pity. Crying for Our Elders advances current discussions on humanitarianism, children's studies, orphanhood, and kinship. By exploring the unique experience of AIDS orphanhood through the eyes of children, caregivers, and policymakers, Cheney shows that despite the extreme challenges of growing up in the era of HIV/AIDS, the post-ARV generation still holds out hope for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAIDS (Disease)xSocial aspectszUganda. 0aChild welfarezUganda. 0aChildren of AIDS patientszUgandaxSocial conditions. 0aOrphanszUgandaxSocial conditions. 0aPoor childrenzUgandaxSocial conditions. 4aAIDS. 4aAfrica. 4aHIV. 4aOVC. 4achildren's rights. 4achildren. 4ahumanitarianism. 4akinship. 4aorphans and vulnerable children. 4apoverty. 4ayouth participatory research. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226437682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226437682.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles